
# E2E test credentials (used by `npm run test:e2e`)
# Create a dedicated test user in Firebase Auth, then fill these in your local .env.
TEST_EMAIL=test@example.com
TEST_PASSWORD=replace-with-test-user-password

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Fallback / break-glass admin account
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# This app deliberately has NO code-level fallback login — that was
# the exact vulnerability removed in the security pass (anyone could
# set localStorage.setItem("lotus.session.email", "...") and become admin).
#
# To create a real fallback admin user:
#   1. Open the Firebase console → Authentication → Users → Add user.
#   2. Email: e.g. admin-fallback@<your-domain>
#      Password: a strong, unique value stored in your password manager.
#   3. (Optional) Enable MFA for that user under Authentication → Settings.
#   4. Sign in via the normal /login form using those credentials.
#
# Treat this like a root-of-trust account: do NOT reuse it for daily work,
# rotate it after any team member leaves, and audit its usage from the
# Security Log page.
